    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-07-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-07-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="231"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d231">
                <head>231. Memorandum From the Under Secretary of State (<persName corresp="#p_HHJ1"
                        type="from">Hoover</persName>) to the Assistant to the President (<persName
                        corresp="#p_AS1" type="to">Adams</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d231fn1">Source: Department of State, Central Files, 103–<gloss
                            target="#t_XMB1">XMB</gloss>/7–1356. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-07-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 13, 1956</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Export-Import Bank Credits for the Last Six Months of 1956</item>
                </list>
                <p>I understand that the Export-Import Bank has been asked to determine how their
                    activities may affect the business outlook for the remainder of the year. Policy
                    decisions by the Department of State quite naturally affect the Bank’s
                    operations. In general, the Department has supported a more active Export-Import
                    Bank both in the interests of our foreign policy and the American business
                    community.</p>
                <p>There is one instance which I believe may be brought to your attention where
                    there is an exception to this general rule, again for foreign policy reasons. We
                    have thought that some delay—a slow down—in credits to the Government of Mexico
                    would have a beneficial effect upon our efforts to obtain an aviation agreement
                    with Mexico. The leverage we can exert in this matter is limited and <pb
                        facs="0765" n="731" xml:id="pg_731"/> we want to make the best use of the
                    tools at our disposal. We have asked the Bank to cooperate with us in this
                    endeavor. We have already detected some signs of progress towards the agreement
                    and believe that the Bank’s natural desire to make more loans will not be
                    seriously or long impeded by this exception to general policy. On the other
                    hand, the aviation agreement when obtained will have many beneficial results
                    outweighing considerably, we believe, the temporary disadvantage.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HHJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Herbert Hoover, Jr</hi>
                        </persName>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
